Introduction

Disaster struck Haiti in 2010, whereby a destructive earthquake left many people homeless and in need of food, water, and shelter. Rescue workers from the US military are in charge of delivering supplies to the people in need. This project aims to process the high-resolution imagery taken by the RIT aircraft to locate the blue tarps that indicate the presence of survivors. The project utilizes several data-mining approaches, whereby it sets up the models, trains them, and compares them to arrive at the best model suited for this task.

As seen from the probability table, blue tarps consist only 3.19% of the observations, whereby vegetation and soil consist the majority.

Model Training

Set-up

No scaling will be done, since the RGB values have the same range. Since the goal is to classify as blue tarp or not (i.e. we don’t care if it’s soil or vegetation or etc.), I will create a new binary column named BlueTarp which will act as the output variable of interest.

haiti_training = dummy_cols(haiti_training, select_columns = c("Class"))
haiti_training = filter(haiti_training) %>% select(c("Class_Blue Tarp","Red","Green","Blue"))
haiti_training = rename(haiti_training,"Blue_Tarp" = "Class_Blue Tarp")
haiti_training_nolabel = select(haiti_training, -Blue_Tarp)
# Setting up the data
X.train = filter(haiti_training) %>% select(-c("Blue_Tarp")) %>%as.matrix()
Y.train = haiti_training$Blue_Tarp


n = nrow(haiti_training) # number of training observations
n.folds = 10 # number of folds for cross-validation
set.seed(2021) # set seed for reproducibility

Logistic Regression

For logistic regression, I implemented 10-fold CV using a loop. I collected the results of the loop at the end. The performance metrics of interest are stored in a tibble to later on plot the ROC curve and derive the threshold. There are no parameters to tune here.

set.seed(2021)
fold = sample(rep(1:n.folds, length=n)) # I will use the same sampling for all models.

G.truth = vector()
LR_RESULTS = tibble()

for(j in 1:n.folds){
  #-- Set training/val data
  val = which(fold == j) # indices of holdout/validation data
  train = which(fold != j) # indices of fitting/training data
  n.val = length(val) # number of observations in validation
  G.test = haiti_training$Blue_Tarp[val]
  data_fit = slice(haiti_training, train)
  data_eval = slice(haiti_training, val)
  #- fit and evaluate models
  fit.lr = glm(Blue_Tarp ~ Red + Green + Blue, data = data_fit, 
             family="binomial")
  prob.lr = predict(fit.lr, newdata = data_eval, type="response") # probabilities
  link.lr = predict(fit.lr, newdata = data_eval, type="link")     # logit (linear part)
  results_temp = tibble(prob.lr,link.lr)
  #- update RESULTS
  LR_RESULTS = bind_rows(LR_RESULTS, results_temp)
  G.truth = append(G.truth,G.test)
}

LR_PERF = tibble(truth = G.truth, gamma = LR_RESULTS$link.lr, p.hat = LR_RESULTS$prob.lr) %>% 
  #- group_by() + summarize() in case of ties
  group_by(gamma, p.hat) %>%     
  summarize(n=n(), n.1=sum(truth), n.0=n-sum(truth)) %>% ungroup() %>% 
  #- calculate metrics
  arrange(gamma) %>% 
  mutate(FN = cumsum(n.1),    # false negatives 
         TN = cumsum(n.0),    # true negatives
         TP = sum(n.1) - FN,  # true positives
         FP = sum(n.0) - TN,  # false positives
         N = cumsum(n),       # number of cases predicted to be 1
         TPR = TP/sum(n.1), FPR = FP/sum(n.0)) %>% 
  #- only keep relevant metrics
  select(-n, -n.1, -n.0, gamma, p.hat)

LR_RESULTS = tibble(truth = G.truth, gamma = LR_RESULTS$link.lr, p.hat = LR_RESULTS$prob.lr)

KNN

For the KNN model, I only have one parameter to tune, which is \(k\). Given the relatively big observation set, I suspect that we won’t run into the same problem that occurred in HW2, where a non-optimal \(k\) was picked by cross validation due to the data set’s relatively small size of 100 observations. I searched over the range of \(k\) [3,50]. The choice of range was arbitrary. In my implementation, I used the \(knn3()\) function, predicted the probabilities of the evaluation set using \(predict()\), and captured the probabilities of detecting class 1. It could be done using \(knn()\) or \(knn.reg()\) functions, but I like this approach because it shows what I’m doing step by step. In order to pick the optimal \(k\), I will use the AUROC since it is one of the metrics in the performance table.

#- Initialize
set.seed(2021) 
K = 3:50                                # set of k values for kNN
n.val = numeric(n.folds)                # number of elements in validation sets
columns = c("Red","Green","Blue","Blue_Tarp")
levs = c("1", "0")

KNN_RESULTS = tibble()
AUROC_KNN = tibble()

#-- fit set of knn models
for(i in 1:length(K)){
  k = K[i]

  #- Iterate over folds
    for(j in 1:n.folds){
    
    #-- Set training/val data
    val = which(fold == j)
    train = which(fold != j)
    n.val[j] = length(val)
    
    knn = knn3(Blue_Tarp ~ ., data = haiti_training[train,columns, drop=FALSE], k = k)
    prob.knn = predict(knn, newdata = haiti_training[val,columns, drop=FALSE], type="prob") # probabilities
    prob.knn = prob.knn[,2] #Probabilities of class 1, which is detecting Blue Tarp
    G.test = haiti_training$Blue_Tarp[val] #The truth values used for evaluation
    
    results = tibble(truth = G.test, prob.knn)
    KNN_RESULTS = bind_rows(KNN_RESULTS,results)
    
    }
  # For each k, I will calculate the AUROC.    
  auroc = KNN_RESULTS %>% 
  yardstick::roc_auc(truth = factor(truth, levels=levs), estimate = prob.knn)
  auroc_temp = tibble(k = k,auroc = auroc$.estimate)
  AUROC_KNN = bind_rows(AUROC_KNN,auroc_temp)
  KNN_RESULTS = tibble() #Empty the tibble
}

AUROC_KNN$k[AUROC_KNN$auroc==max(AUROC_KNN$auroc)]
#> [1] 39

Based on the results above,\(k_{optimal} = 39\). Next, we perform cross validation using \(k_{optimal}\) and store our performance metrics of interest in a tibble to later on plot the ROC curve and derive the threshold.

Penalized Logistic Regression (ElasticNet)

When it comes to penalized logistic regression, I have to tune parameters \(\lambda\) and \(\alpha\).I will fit and find \(\lambda_{min}\) that minimizes the cross validation error which is why I won’t consider \(\lambda_{1SE}\), but I will compare for the sake of proof. To do that, I put the \(type.measure = deviance\) to use the log-loss function as my loss function.

set.seed(2021) 
#To find optimal lambda

alpha = 1

pred_data = tibble()

#Use 10-fold CV to estimate lambda

fit = cv.glmnet(x = X.train, y=Y.train,alpha=alpha, family="binomial",type.measure="deviance",foldid=fold)
min(fit$cvm)
#> [1] 0.02812682
lambda_min = fit$lambda.min

pred_temp = 
  tibble(
    lambdamin = predict(fit, s="lambda.min", newx=X.train, type="link")[,1], 
    lambda1se = predict(fit, s="lambda.1se", newx=X.train, type="link")[,1], 
    linked = Y.train%>% factor(levels=c(1,0)))
pred_data = bind_rows(pred_data,pred_temp)

pred_data= pred_data %>%
  gather(model, prediction, lambdamin, lambda1se) %>% 
  group_by(model) %>%

#Plot ROC Curve
pred_data %>%

  geom_path() +

  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 1, by=.2)) +

\(\lambda_{min} = 5.5*10^{-6}\). As we can see from the ROC curves, \(\lambda_{min}\) is slightly better for a certain set of thresholds, which is why I will use it instead of \(\lambda_{1SE}\).

For the \(\alpha\) parameter, I will perform a grid search from 0 to 1 to find the \(\alpha\) that minimizes the CVM given \(\lambda_{min}\). I could have used AUROC as the performance metric similar to what I’ve done in KNN, but I decided not to because it was too time consuming. The step choice of 0.1 is arbitrary.I could have chosen a smaller step size such as 0.01, but I didn’t want the loop to take too much computing time.

#To find optimal alpha

set.seed(2021)   
K = 10           # number of folds

#-- Function that returns the minimum cross validation error according to the log loss function for a given alpha
est_cvm <- function(alpha, folds){
  min(cv.glmnet(X.train, Y.train, foldid = fold, alpha=alpha, family="binomial",type.measure="deviance")$cvm)
}

#-- Set alpha sequence
alpha.seq = seq(0, 1, by=.1)

#-- estimate scores
CVM = sapply(alpha.seq, est_cvm, folds=fold)

#-- Plot results
qplot(alpha.seq, CVM)

min(CVM)
#> [1] 0.02812682

Based on the plot, \(\alpha_{optimal} = 1\), which makes it a lasso model.Thus, the final penalized logistic regression model will be the one below, having \(\lambda_{min} =5.5*10^{-6}\), and \(\alpha_{optimal} = 1\). The metrics of interest are stored in a tibble to later on plot the ROC curve and derive the threshold.

Support Vector Machines (SVM)

In the case of SVM, we have 2 parameters to tune: cost and \(\gamma\). I will create a function that fits, predicts, evaluates an SVM model and outputs probabilities. I will loop this to create the 10-fold CV. After I find the best tuning parameters, I will train a SVM model using these parameters and use its results to calculate performance metrics.

tune_grid = expand_grid(
  cost = 10^(-2:2),
  gamma = c(.1, .5, 1))

eval_svm <- function(data_train, data_test, cost, gamma){
  
  #fit
  fit = svm(factor(Blue_Tarp) ~ Red + Green + Blue, 
            data = data_train,
            #: tuning parameters
            kernel = "radial",
            gamma = gamma,
            cost = cost
            )
  
  #predict
  pred = predict(fit, data_test, decision.values = TRUE)
  
  #: evaluate
  eval_data = tibble(
    outcome = data_test$Blue_Tarp, 
    pred_hard = c(pred), 
    pred_soft = as.numeric(attr(pred, "decision.values"))
  )
  
  auroc = eval_data %>% 
    yardstick::roc_auc(truth = factor(outcome, levels=levs), estimate = pred_soft)
  
  accuracy = eval_data %>% 
      yardstick::accuracy(truth = factor(outcome, levels=levs), 
                          estimate = factor(pred_hard, levels=levs))
  
  bind_rows(auroc, accuracy) %>% 
    mutate(cost, gamma)  # add tuning parameters
}

out = tibble()

for(j in n.folds){
  
  for(i in 1:nrow(tune_grid)){
    val = which(fold == j) # indices of holdout/validation data
    train = which(fold != j) # indices of fitting/training data
    
    metrics = eval_svm(
      data_train = slice(haiti_training,train),
      data_test = slice(haiti_training,val),
      cost = tune_grid$cost[i], 
      gamma = tune_grid$gamma[i]
    )
    
    out = bind_rows(out, metrics %>% mutate(fold = j) )
  }
}

#: average over folds

out %>% 
  # calculate average performance over folds 
  group_by(.metric, cost, gamma) %>% 
  summarize(mu = mean(.estimate), .groups = "drop") %>% 
  # spread data wider to see both metrics 
  pivot_wider(names_from = .metric, values_from = mu) %>% 
  # arrange by auc and then accuracy (if ties)
  arrange(desc(roc_auc), desc(accuracy))

Based on the results above, we will go with \(cost = 0.1\) and \(\gamma = 0.1\). The reason I didn’t go with the topmost row is because I don’t want to solely prioritize AUROC as my criterion, so I went with parameters that provided good AUROC and accuracy. \(eval_svm1()\) is similar to the \(eval_svm()\) function above but outputs probabilities which I will use to create the performance metrics tibble SVM_PERF.

cost_optimal = 0.1
gamma_optimal = 0.1

eval_svm1 <- function(data_train, data_test, cost, gamma){
  
  #fit
  fit = svm(factor(Blue_Tarp) ~ Red + Green + Blue, 
            data = data_train,
            #: tuning parameters
            kernel = "radial",
            gamma = gamma,
            cost = cost,
            probability = TRUE)
  
    #predict
  pred = predict(fit, slice(haiti_training,val), probability = TRUE)
  preds = attributes(pred)$probabilities[,2]
  gamma = log(preds)/(1-preds)

  eval_data = tibble(
    truth = data_test$Blue_Tarp, 
    gamma = gamma,
    p.hat = c(pred)
  )

}

Naive Bayes

For Naive Bayes, there are no parameters to tune. I implemented 10-fold CV using a loop.

set.seed(2021)

BAYES_RESULTS = tibble()
for(j in n.folds){
  
  val = which(fold == j) # indices of holdout/validation data
  train = which(fold != j) # indices of fitting/training data

  #fit
  bayes = e1071::naiveBayes(factor(Blue_Tarp) ~ Red + Green + Blue, 
            data = slice(haiti_training,train))    
  #predict
  val_temp = slice(haiti_training,val)
  truth_temp = slice(haiti_training,val)$Blue_Tarp
  pred_temp = predict(bayes, val_temp, type="raw")
  preds = pred_temp[,2]
  gamma_temp = log(preds)/(preds)
  
  results_temp = tibble(p.hat = preds[1:6324],truth =truth_temp,gamma = gamma_temp[1:6324])
  BAYES_RESULTS = bind_rows(BAYES_RESULTS,results_temp)
}

Random Forest

As discussed in HW 6, the most influential parameter to tune is mtry. For the sake of computation time and as discussed in HW 6, ntree should only be set large enough, so I won’t tune it. Due to the limitations of my laptop, I couldn’t push ntree beyond 1,000 (failed to allocate vector of size 1.3 Gb) nor go for 10 folds, so I will go for 5 folds. I concatenated the predictions for all 5 folds and calculated 1 AUROC value per mtry. Based on AUROC, the optimal tuning parameters are \(mtry = 2\), \(ntree = 1000\).

Y.train = haiti_training$Blue_Tarp
haiti_training1 = haiti_training
# Outcomes should be made as factors so that the RF becomes a classification forest.
haiti_training1$Class = as.factor(haiti_training$Blue_Tarp)

set.seed(2021)   
K = 5           # number of folds
ntree = 1000
mtry_seq = seq(1, 3, by=1)  # grid of tuning parameters

RF_RESULTS = tibble()
RF_PERF = tibble()
for (mtry in mtry_seq){
    for(k in 1:K){
      set.seed(2021)
      test = (fold == k)
      train = (fold != k)
      rf = randomForest::randomForest(Class ~ ., data = haiti_training1[train, ],mtry = mtry, ntree = ntree)  
      phat = predict(rf, haiti_training1[test, ],type="prob")
      rf_temp = tibble(mtry = mtry,ntree = ntree,fold = k,truth = haiti_training1[test,]$Class , phat = phat[,2])
      RF_RESULTS = bind_rows(RF_RESULTS,rf_temp)
    }
        # For each mtry, I will calculate the AUROC and pick the optimal tuning parameters based on it.    
      auroc = RF_RESULTS %>% 
      yardstick::roc_auc(truth = factor(truth, levels=levs), estimate = phat)
      auroc_temp = tibble(mtry = mtry,auroc = auroc$.estimate)
      RF_PERF = bind_rows(RF_PERF,auroc_temp)
      RF_RESULTS = tibble() #Empty the tibble
}
AUROC = RF_PERF[1,]$auroc

Now, we train the optimal model to find the performance metrics.

K = 10
mtry_opt = 2
ntree_opt = 1000
P.truth = vector() #I'm saving this to use it in the performance metric calculations,because I found that the truth labels as factors were problematic in calculating the metrics.
RF_p.hat = vector()
for(k in 1:K){
    set.seed(2021)
    test = (fold == k)
    train = (fold != k)
    rf_opt = randomForest::randomForest(Class ~ ., data = haiti_training1[train, ],mtry = mtry_opt, ntree = ntree_opt)  
    phat = predict(rf_opt, haiti_training1[test, ],type="prob")
    rf_temp = phat[,2]
    RF_p.hat = append(RF_p.hat,rf_temp)
    truth = truth = haiti_training[test,]$Blue_Tarp
    P.truth = append(P.truth,truth)
}

gamma = log((RF_p.hat)/(1-RF_p.hat))

RF_RESULTS = tibble(truth = P.truth, p.hat = RF_p.hat, gamma)
RF_PERF = RF_RESULTS %>% group_by(gamma,p.hat) %>%     
  summarize(n=n(), n.1=sum(truth), n.0=n-sum(truth)) %>% ungroup() %>% 
  #- calculate metrics
  arrange(gamma) %>% 
  mutate(FN = cumsum(n.1),    # false negatives 
         TN = cumsum(n.0),    # true negatives
         TP = sum(n.1) - FN,  # true positives
         FP = sum(n.0) - TN,  # false positives
         N = cumsum(n),       # number of cases predicted to be 1
         TPR = TP/sum(n.1), FPR = FP/sum(n.0)) %>% 
  #- only keep relevant metrics
  select(-n, -n.1, -n.0,gamma,p.hat)

Boosted Trees

I will be using the XGBoost algorithm. The tuning parameters are learning rate and number of rounds. I will perform a grid search to find the optimal learning rate and number of rounds. The metric for the XGBoost will be AUROC. Max depth has been arbitrarily set to 3. Based on our grid search, the optimal parameters are \(eta = 0.07\) , \(nrounds = 700\).

set.seed(2021)
tune_grid = expand_grid(
  nb_rounds = seq(100, 1000, by=200),
  eta = seq(0.01, 0.1, by=0.02))

out = tibble()
BOOST_AUROC = tibble()

for(i in 1:nrow(tune_grid)){

    xgb = xgboost::xgb.cv(
      data = as.matrix(X.train),
      label = Y.train,
      eta = tune_grid$eta[i],
      nrounds = tune_grid$nb_rounds[i],
      max_depth = 3,
      objective = "binary:logistic",
      nfold = 10,
      prediction = TRUE,
      metrics = "auc",
      verbose = FALSE
      )
    
      xgb_pred = xgb$pred
      out = tibble(Y.train,xgb_pred)
      auroc = out %>% 
      yardstick::roc_auc(truth = factor(Y.train, levels=levs), estimate = xgb_pred)
      auroc_temp = tibble(eta = tune_grid$eta[i],nrounds = tune_grid$nb_rounds[i],auroc = auroc$.estimate)
      BOOST_AUROC  = bind_rows(BOOST_AUROC,auroc_temp)
      out = tibble()
}

Now, we perform cross validation to report the performance metrics.

eta_opt = 0.07
nrounds_opt = 700

set.seed(2021)
xgb_opt = xgboost::xgb.cv(
    data = as.matrix(X.train),
    label = Y.train,
    eta = eta_opt,
    nrounds = nrounds_opt,
    max_depth = 3,
    objective = "binary:logistic",
    nfold = 10,
    prediction = TRUE,
    metrics = "auc",
    verbose = FALSE
    )

xgb_pred_opt = xgb_opt$pred
BOOST_gamma = log((xgb_pred_opt)/(1-xgb_pred_opt))
BOOST_RESULTS = tibble(truth = Y.train, p.hat = xgb_pred_opt, gamma = BOOST_gamma)
BOOST_PERF = BOOST_RESULTS%>% 
  group_by(gamma,p.hat) %>% 
  summarize(n=n(), n.1=sum(truth), n.0=n-sum(truth)) %>% ungroup() %>% 
  #- calculate metrics
  arrange(gamma) %>% 
  mutate(FN = cumsum(n.1),    # false negatives 
         TN = cumsum(n.0),    # true negatives
         TP = sum(n.1) - FN,  # true positives
         FP = sum(n.0) - TN,  # false positives
         N = cumsum(n),       # number of cases predicted to be 1
         TPR = TP/sum(n.1), FPR = FP/sum(n.0)) %>% 
  #- only keep relevant metrics
  select(-n, -n.1, -n.0,gamma,p.hat)

Threshold Selection

As can be seen from the parts above, I created ranges of thresholds for each model. Each row in each of the tibbles LR_PERF, KNN_PERF, ENET_PERF, and SVM_PERF represents the performance metrics according to a given threshold. Naturally, we want a threshold that maximizes the TPR while minimizing the FPR. For example, a threshold that yields 1 TPR but 1 FPR isn’t really useful, for it means that the model is labeling everything as true (or 1). A threshold that, for example, yields 0.999 TPR and 0.15 FPR is a better threshold.

We can choose arbitrary values for \(C_{FP}\) and \(C_{FN}\), and calculate a theoretical optimal threshold. In this case, I will set \(C_{FP} = 1\) and \(C_{FN} = 6\), since I see that the cost of a false negative (not helping someone in need) is more precious than falsely identifying a blue tarp. Based on my arbitrary values, the threshold becomes \(\frac{1}{1+6} = \frac{1}{7} = 0.1428\). Thus, my threshold is \(p =~0.1428\).

  select(-n, -n.1, -n.0,gamma,p.hat)
  
#KNN
  
  prob.knn = predict(knn, newdata = HoldOut[,columns], type="prob") #   probabilities
  prob.knn = prob.knn[,2] #Probabilities of class 1, which is detecting Blue Tarp
  gamma.knn = log((prob.knn)/(1-prob.knn))
  KNN_HOLDOUT = tibble(truth = truth_HOLDOUT , p.hat = prob.knn, gamma = gamma.knn)
  
  KNN_PERF_HOLDOUT = KNN_HOLDOUT%>% 
  group_by(gamma,p.hat) %>% 
  summarize(n=n(), n.1=sum(truth), n.0=n-sum(truth)) %>% ungroup() %>% 
  #- calculate metrics
  arrange(gamma) %>% 
  mutate(FN = cumsum(n.1),    # false negatives 
         TN = cumsum(n.0),    # true negatives
         TP = sum(n.1) - FN,  # true positives
         FP = sum(n.0) - TN,  # false positives
         N = cumsum(n),       # number of cases predicted to be 1
         TPR = TP/sum(n.1), FPR = FP/sum(n.0)) %>% 
  #- only keep relevant metrics
  select(-n, -n.1, -n.0,gamma,p.hat)

Conclusions

Conclusion #1

Analyzing both the CV and holdout performance tables, the optimized RF model is the best. Looking at AUROC, accuracy, TPR, and FPR, an argument could be made for other models such as SVM or KNN, but what set the RF model apart from the others was its precision. While all other models significantly dipped in precision, the RF model maintained an almost perfect precision.

Conclusion #2

The findings above can be considered valid, since the models’ parameters were optimized, and the Hold Out data was several magnitudes greater than the training data, which allows us to assess how the models would’ve performed in the real world. Had the testing data been much smaller than the training data, the findings wouldn’t have been as representative and valid.

Conclusion #3

I would recommend the RF model for detection of blue tarps since it outperforms all other models according to the metrics used. I believe the nature of trees and how they divide the feature space is an advantage in this case, especially since blue is one of the variables.

Conclusion #4

The performance table above showed that we cannot rely on a single metric to assess our models’ performance. For example, had we relied solely on accuracy, it would’ve appeared that Naive Bayes and RF are quite similar in performance, but looking at the other metrics shows that RF is indeed superior.

Conclusion #5

It seems that the classifiers (Bayes, LDA, QDA) were unimpressive in this context, and this may indicate that they aren’t well suited for this task. This may have to do with the data distribution.

Conclusion #6

I found it interesting that almost all the models preserved their accuracy, AUROC, TPR, and FPR numbers, but their precision numbers significantly fell. Low precision means that the classifier returns a lot of false positives (falsely classifying a portion as Blue Tarp). Going back to the costs that we allocated (\(C_{FP} = 1\) and \(C_{FN} = 6\)), low precision may not be a significant issue, so models other than RF may be considered appropriate if forced to pick something else.However, recall that my choice of costs was arbitrary, so a different cost assignment may deem precision more crucial and give an even bigger edge to the RF model.

Conclusion #7

I believe the fall in precision has to do with the data composition of the HoldOut data. Blue_Tarp was already relatively rare in the training data (~3%), and it was even rarer in the testing data (~0.7%). This definitely has an impact on precision.

Conclusion #8

Regarding the Naive Bayes classifier (which was clearly the worst performer of the 9), perhaps the data distribution and the nature of the task isn’t suitable. According to the R documentation of the naiveBayes function, the implementation assumes gaussian distribution of the metric predictors and independence of the predictor variables. It might’ve performed better with a more balanced dataset, or in a problem involving multiclasses, historical prediction, or text classification. Perhaps a different implementation of the Bayes classifier (such as multinomial Bayes) would’ve shown much better performance as well.
